Now I have a thorough understanding of all the relevant code. Let me compile my findings.

---

Here are my efficiency findings for the `feat/ignore-list` branch, reviewing only production files:

---

## Finding 1: `IgnoreStore.has()` is O(n) on the chat hot path

**File:** `/home/openclaw/code/tuicraft/src/wow/ignore-store.ts`, lines 62-67  
**Called from:** `/home/openclaw/code/tuicraft/src/wow/world-handlers.ts`, line 83

```typescript
has(guidLow: number): boolean {
  for (const guid of this.ignored.keys()) {
    if (Number(guid & 0xffffffffn) === guidLow) return true;
  }
  return false;
}
```

This method does a linear scan over every entry in the ignore map, computing `Number(guid & 0xffffffffn)` on each iteration. It is called in `resolveAndDeliver` (line 83 of `world-handlers.ts`), which runs on **every incoming chat message** -- the hottest path in the application.

The fix would be to maintain a secondary `Map<number, bigint>` (or `Set<number>`) keyed by `guidLow`, updated in `set()`, `add()`, and `remove()`. This would make `has()` O(1). The `FriendStore` does not have this problem because it does not have a `has(guidLow)` method on the hot path.

**Impact: Medium.** WoW ignore lists are server-capped at 50 entries, so n is bounded and small. The linear scan over 50 bigints with a bitmask per iteration is measurably costlier than a Map lookup but still fast in absolute terms (microseconds). On a busy server with heavy chat spam, the constant-factor overhead adds up but is unlikely to become a bottleneck before other things (socket I/O, packet parsing) dominate.

**Worth fixing: Yes.** It is a trivial fix (add a `Set<number>` index) that turns O(n) into O(1) on the hottest path, with essentially no cost to maintain.

---

## Finding 2: `IgnoreStore.all()` allocates, copies, and sorts on every `handleNameQueryResponse`

**File:** `/home/openclaw/code/tuicraft/src/wow/ignore-store.ts`, lines 69-73  
**Called from:** `/home/openclaw/code/tuicraft/src/wow/world-handlers.ts`, lines 151-155

```typescript
all(): IgnoreEntry[] {
  return [...this.ignored.values()].sort((a, b) =>
    a.name.localeCompare(b.name),
  );
}
```

In `handleNameQueryResponse` (lines 151-155), `conn.ignoreStore.all()` is called to find entries whose name has not yet been resolved:

```typescript
for (const entry of conn.ignoreStore.all()) {
  if (Number(entry.guid & 0xffffffffn) === result.guidLow && !entry.name) {
    conn.ignoreStore.setName(entry.guid, result.name);
  }
}
```

`handleNameQueryResponse` runs every time a name query resolves -- potentially dozens of times at login as entities and friend/ignore entries get their names populated. Each call allocates a new array, copies all entries, then sorts them by name -- but the sort order is irrelevant here because the caller just does a linear scan looking for a matching guidLow.

The same pattern exists for `friendStore.all()` (lines 143-149) and `entityStore.all()` (line 134) in the same function. However, those are pre-existing patterns and not introduced by this branch. The ignore-list branch adds a third instance.

**Impact: Low.** Ignore lists are capped at 50 entries. The allocation + sort is O(n log n) but with n <= 50 and `localeCompare` it is still very fast. The real waste is the sort being completely unnecessary in this context.

**Worth fixing: Marginal.** Adding an unsorted iteration method (e.g., `values()` that returns the raw Map iterator) for internal use in `handleNameQueryResponse` would avoid unnecessary allocations and sorting. However, this is not performance-critical given the small n. If the pattern is going to be replicated for more stores in the future, it would be worth establishing the right convention now.

---

## Finding 3: `handleContactList` iterates `list.contacts` twice

**File:** `/home/openclaw/code/tuicraft/src/wow/world-handlers.ts`, lines 525-568

The function iterates `list.contacts` once for friends (lines 528-549) and again for ignored entries (lines 553-567). Both loops do the same `nameCache` lookup and name-query dedup logic, and a contact could have both `FRIEND` and `IGNORED` flags (unusual but allowed by the bitmask protocol).

A single pass could extract both friends and ignored entries simultaneously.

**Impact: Low.** This runs once at login. The contact list is typically under 100 entries. Two passes over a small array is negligible.

**Worth fixing: No.** The two-loop structure is easier to read and mirrors the separation of concerns between `FriendStore` and `IgnoreStore`. The single-login cost is immaterial.

---

## Finding 4: No explicit clearing of `IgnoreStore` (and `FriendStore`) on disconnect

**File:** `/home/openclaw/code/tuicraft/src/wow/client.ts`, lines 720-725

The socket `close()` handler calls `conn.entityStore.clear()` but does not clear `friendStore` or `ignoreStore`:

```typescript
close() {
  clearInterval(pingInterval);
  conn.entityStore.clear();
  if (!done) reject(new Error("World connection closed"));
  closedResolve();
},
```

Meanwhile, the `handle.close()` method (lines 455-461) nullifies the event callbacks (`onIgnoreEvent`, `onFriendEvent`, `onEntityEvent`) but does not clear the stores themselves.

After disconnection, the `WorldConn` object holds stale `IgnoreStore` and `FriendStore` instances with their data. Since the entire `WorldConn` is scoped to the `worldSession()` closure and no external references escape beyond the `WorldHandle` (which only exposes methods, not the conn itself), the stores will be garbage collected when the handle goes out of scope.

The entity store is explicitly cleared because `clear()` fires `disappear` events for every entity, which the listener needs to process before teardown. The friend/ignore stores have no equivalent "disconnect" event requirement.

**Impact: Low.** No actual memory leak -- the stores are GC'd with the connection. The stale data is not observable because `handle.close()` calls `socket.end()` which triggers the socket close handler, which resolves `closed`, which causes the daemon to exit (or the caller to drop the handle).

**Worth fixing: No.** The current behavior is correct. Adding explicit `clear()` calls would fire unnecessary `ignore-list`/`friend-list` events during teardown when the listeners have already been nullified.

---

## Finding 5: `handleNameQueryResponse` does three separate linear scans over three stores

**File:** `/home/openclaw/code/tuicraft/src/wow/world-handlers.ts`, lines 134-156

```typescript
for (const entity of conn.entityStore.all()) { ... }
for (const friend of conn.friendStore.all()) { ... }
for (const entry of conn.ignoreStore.all()) { ... }
```

Each of these calls `all()`, which allocates a new sorted array. Then each iterates the full array doing `Number(entry.guid & 0xffffffffn) === result.guidLow` on every element.

This is a pre-existing pattern for entities and friends, but the ignore-list branch adds a third loop. All three could be addressed by maintaining a reverse index from `guidLow` to `guid` in each store, but that is a broader refactor.

**Impact: Low.** Name query responses arrive at login for dozens of entities/friends/ignores, but each store is small. The three separate sorted-array allocations are wasteful but not practically significant.

**Worth fixing: Only if Finding 1 is addressed.** If a `guidLow` index is added to `IgnoreStore` for the `has()` hot path fix, the same index could be used here to make `setName` an O(1) lookup. But this is not urgent on its own.

---

## Finding 6: `IgnoreStore.set()` creates shallow copies that may be unnecessary

**File:** `/home/openclaw/code/tuicraft/src/wow/ignore-store.ts`, lines 24-33

```typescript
set(entries: IgnoreEntry[]): void {
  this.ignored.clear();
  for (const entry of entries) {
    this.ignored.set(entry.guid, { ...entry });
  }
  this.listener?.({
    type: "ignore-list",
    entries: [...this.ignored.values()],
  });
}
```

The spread `{ ...entry }` creates a defensive copy, and then `[...this.ignored.values()]` creates another array copy for the event. This mirrors the existing `FriendStore.set()` pattern.

**Impact: Negligible.** The ignore list is max 50 entries and `set()` is called once at login.

**Worth fixing: No.** The defensive copies prevent aliasing bugs and match the project convention.

---

## Summary Table

| # | File | Issue | Impact | Fix? |
|---|------|-------|--------|------|
| 1 | `ignore-store.ts:62-67` | `has()` is O(n) on chat hot path | Medium | **Yes** |
| 2 | `ignore-store.ts:69-73` | `all()` allocates + sorts unnecessarily in `handleNameQueryResponse` | Low | Marginal |
| 3 | `world-handlers.ts:525-568` | `handleContactList` iterates contacts twice | Low | No |
| 4 | `client.ts:720-725` | No explicit `IgnoreStore` clear on disconnect | Low | No |
| 5 | `world-handlers.ts:134-156` | Three separate sorted-array scans in name query handler | Low | Only with #1 |
| 6 | `ignore-store.ts:24-33` | Defensive copies in `set()` | Negligible | No |

**The one finding I recommend fixing is #1**: adding a `Set<number>` secondary index keyed by `guidLow` to make `has()` O(1). The WoW ignore list cap of 50 means this is not an emergency, but it is the right data structure for the job and trivial to implement. Everything else is either not worth the code churn or only marginally beneficial given the protocol-imposed size limits.

